  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Eternal Jade
  author: Jeong Mongju
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A sea stone, cunningly polished and refined,
    A monk brings it from distant lands to me.
    When I exhale upon its face, cold clouds arise,
    Water fills the inkwell, a crescent moon slants through.

    Wherever it is touched, like precious metal it rings,
    Washed clean, a flawless sphere without a blemish.
    At dawn beneath the autumn window,
    I dip my brush, and suddenly—poetry swells tenfold.
  footnotes:
    - The inkstone, fashioned from sea stone, is personified as a precious object that responds to the poet's touch and breath.
    - The 'crescent moon' refers to the reflection on the surface of water in the inkwell—a common image in East Asian literati culture representing the marriage of natural beauty and human refinement.
    - The poem moves from physical description to the transformative moment of creative inspiration, suggesting that material objects can awaken the spirit of poetic composition.
